results.name: Number of primes with n distinct decimal digits, none of which are 0.
comment: a(9) is zero because 1+2+...+9 = 45 which is divisible by 3, making any number with 9 distinct digits also divisible by 3. - _Wei Zhou_, Oct 02 2011
The maximal distinct-digit prime without 0's is 98765431. Thus, a(n) = 0 for n >= 9. - _Michael S. Branicky_, Apr 20 2021
example: a(2) = #{13,17,19,23,...,97} = 20. Note that the prime 11 is omitted because its decimal digits are not distinct.
mathematica: Length /@ Table[Select[FromDigits /@ Permutations[Range@9, {i}], PrimeQ], {i,9}] (* _Wei Zhou_, Oct 02 2011 *)
program: def distinct_digs(n): s = str(n); return len(s) == len(set(s))
return sum(isprime(int("".join(p))) for p in permutations("123456789", n))
print([a(n) for n in range(1, 30)]) # _Michael S. Branicky_, Apr 20 2021
